fr:mainmatter.fr:p: A global element of an object X in a cartesian closed category (or sometimes more generally a closed monoidal category, in which case the same concept is sometimes called a generalized element or state) is a morphism 1\to X.

fr:mainmatter.fr:p: We dedicate this book to the memory of J. Frank Adams. His clear insights have inspired many mathematicians, including both of us. In January 1989, when the first draft of our book had been completed, we heard the sad news of his untimely death. This has cast a shadow on our subsequent work. Our views of topos theory, as presented here, have been shaped by continued study, by conferences, and by many personal contacts with friends and colleagues-including especially O. Bruno, P. Freyd, J.M.E. Hyland, P.T. Johnstone, A. Joyal, A. Kock, F.W. Lawvere, G.E. Reyes, R Solovay, R Swan, RW. Thomason, M. Tierney, and G.C. Wraith. Our presentation combines ideas and results from these people and from many others, but we have not endeavored to specify the various original sources. Moreover, a number of people have assisted in our work by pro viding helpful comments on portions of the manuscript. In this respect, we extend our hearty thanks in particular to P. Corazza, K. Edwards, J. Greenlees, G. Janelidze, G. Lewis, and S. Schanuel.
Let \mathcal {V} be a monoidal category. A \mathcal {V}-category C, also called a category enriched in \mathcal {V}, consists of:

fr:ul.fr:li: a collection of objects, overloadingly also called C;
for each pair of objects x, y\in C, an object C(x, y) of \mathcal {V}, called the hom-object;
for every triple of objects x, y, z\in C, a morphism C(y, z)\otimes C(x, y)\xrightarrow {\circ _{x,y,z}} C(x, z), called composition;
for evey object x\in C, a global element I\xrightarrow {1_x} C, called the identity.

fr:mainmatter.fr:p: This data must make the following associativity and unitality diagrams commute:

fr:resource.fr:resource-source: \begin {tikzcd} ( C(z, w)\otimes C(y,z))\otimes C(x, y) & & C(z, w)\otimes ( C(y,z)\otimes C(x, y)) \\ C(y, w)\otimes C(x, y) & C(x, y) & C(z, w)\otimes ( C(x, z)) \\ \arrow ["\alpha _{ C(z, w), C(y,z), C(x, y)}", from=1-1, to=1-3] \arrow ["\circ _{y, z, w}\otimes 1_{ C(x, y)}", from=1-1, to=2-1, swap] \arrow ["1_{ C(z, w)}\otimes \circ _{x, y, z}", from=1-3, to=2-3] \arrow ["\circ _{x, y, w}", from=2-1, to=2-2, swap] \arrow ["\circ _{x, z, w}", from=2-3, to=2-2] \end {tikzcd}

fr:mainmatter.fr:p: A closed monoidal category is a symmetric monoidal category C such that the bifunctor \otimes is closed. Explicitly, this means there is a bifunctor C^\text {op}\times C\xrightarrow {[-, -]} C, called the internal hom, together with a natural isormorphism C(x\otimes y, z)\cong C(x, [y, z]), called currying.
The counit of the adjunction (-\otimes y)\dashv [y, -] is called evaluation: it is a natural transformation [y, x]\otimes y\xrightarrow {\operatorname {ev}} x.

Applying the adjunction with x the monoidal unit I implies that maps y\to z are in natural bijection with maps I\to [y, z]. By the philosophy of generalized elements, this explains the name internal hom: its elements are maps.
A cartesian closed category is a cartesian monoidal category whose monoidal structure is closed. In this case, we call the internal hom [x, y] an exponential object, and write it y^x.

A closed monoidal category is a symmetric monoidal category C such that the bifunctor \otimes is closed. Explicitly, this means there is a bifunctor C^\text {op}\times C\xrightarrow {[-, -]} C, called the internal hom, together with a natural isormorphism C(x\otimes y, z)\cong C(x, [y, z]), called currying.
The counit of the adjunction (-\otimes y)\dashv [y, -] is called evaluation: it is a natural transformation [y, x]\otimes y\xrightarrow {\operatorname {ev}} x.

Applying the adjunction with x the monoidal unit I implies that maps y\to z are in natural bijection with maps I\to [y, z]. By the philosophy of generalized elements, this explains the name internal hom: its elements are maps.
